'''Alistair Morrison Carmichael''' (born [[July 15]], [[1965]]) is a [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat]] politician, and [[Scottish MPs|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Scotland|Scottish]] seat of [[Orkney and Shetland (UK Parliament constituency)|Orkney and Shetland]]. He has been an MP since the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 general election]].

==Political Career== 
Alistair Carmichael is currently a backbench MP.  He was the Liberal Democrat Northern Ireland and Scotland Spokesman until resigning in March 2008.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/senior-lib-dem-referendum-rebel-quits-791747.html Lib Dem trio quit in referendum revolt] - The Independent, 05/03/2006</ref>.  He also briefly served as the Liberal Democrat Home Affairs Spokesman following the resignation of [[Mark Oaten]].

He has campaigned to simplify the forms for claiming child tax credit, saying many are not claiming the benefit due to being put off by the application process.<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/newsfeed/2008/02/05/beating-poverty-a-simple-solution-86908-20309545/ Beating Poverty: A simple Solution] - Daily Record</ref>

Carmichael is a prominent member of the [[centre-left]] [[Beveridge Group]] within the Liberal Democrats, and has argued against the growth of the [[market liberalism|market liberal]] faction within the party (see [[The Orange Book: Reclaiming Liberalism]]).  

==Background and Interests==
He was born on [[Islay]] and received his education at the [[University of Aberdeen]]. He is married with two children and lives in [[Orkney]]. He speaks both [[French language|French]] and [[German language|German]].  He lists his interests as listening to music, theatre and cooking.

